00:00:48.339 --> 00:00:50.450
?
But what exactly happens in those four seconds

00:00:50.450 --> 00:00:52.600
that makes us willing to be anywhere else?

00:00:52.600 --> 00:00:57.059
Well, a social experiment, or as Facebook
calls it: a new feature, was conducted at

00:00:57.059 --> 00:01:01.680
the University of Groningen in the Netherlands,
that showed the importance of conversational

00:01:01.680 --> 00:01:02.680
flow.

00:01:02.680 --> 00:01:07.490
When a conversation is going strong, or riffing
as I like to call it, we experience positive

00:01:07.490 --> 00:01:11.070
emotions, social validation, and a sense of
belonging.

00:01:11.070 --> 00:01:16.160
So it only makes sense that when it's brought
to a screeching halt, or stiffing as I call

00:01:16.160 --> 00:01:19.500
it, we're flooded by feelings of rejection
and ostracism.

00:01:19.500 --> 00:01:24.080
They found this out by having a group of sixty
undergrads watch one of two six-minute videos

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:25.300
of a conversation.

00:01:25.300 --> 00:01:28.380
In both videos one person makes a controversial
remark.

00:01:28.380 --> 00:01:33.070
In one of the videos, the conversation continues
smoothly and moves onto a different topic.

00:01:33.070 --> 00:01:37.650
But in the other video, eeeeerp- the conversation
stops.

00:01:37.650 --> 00:01:42.100
For four seconds of silence, after which the
conversation continues.

00:01:42.100 --> 00:01:50.040
And while the conversation continues the exact
same way in both videos, the silence in between

00:01:50.040 --> 00:01:51.750
made all the difference.

00:01:51.750 --> 00:01:56.430
It disrupted the flow enough to make those
that watched the video with the pause feel

00:01:56.430 --> 00:02:01.190
"more rejection, more negative emotions, and
less positive emotions" which seems a little

00:02:01.190 --> 00:02:03.860
redundant but I wanna give you all the facts.

00:02:03.860 --> 00:02:05.170
You never disrupt the flow.

00:02:05.170 --> 00:02:10.509
